Fleeing from Moscow
The fall of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, the market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke with their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely based on – with active support from Russia – secessionist movements that tried to keep both countries within the “sphere of influence” of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeepers" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn into hot wars.
This has not happened, and now we can speak of solutions – because both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve breakthroughs towards market economy and democracy.
The European Union's "Neighbourhood Policy" also contributed to this.
The starting point for these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
Already dangerously close to failure, Georgia has turned towards the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet bloc countries also sparked change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at rapprochement with the EU.
These changes have spurred new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries in a peaceful manner.
Estonia's experience suggests how Georgia and Moldova should approach their policies towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with immense economic problems that was unsuitable for investment.
Estland was indeed poor, and its most important export products were metal scrap and wood, but its economy was growing.
In North-East Estonia, where the majority of the population consisted of ethnic Russians who had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported what was called an "autonomy movement".
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and interrupted gas supplies.
Taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that could be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its nerve.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country to reorient its economy towards the West.
On the other hand, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic States – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and eventually, Estonia became one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, joining both the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported to the same extent by Western Europe.
Naturally, Georgia appeared as a less attractive partner than the Baltic States; the 1990s were characterized by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, during which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – largely separated with Russian support.
The country has done its best to make its dismal past disappear.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and diligently working to move the country forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – which is likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Bribery is decreasing, and a justice reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and over 10% in 2006.
Georgia is striving to ease tensions regarding Abkhazia and South Ossetia; Russia, however, accuses the country of aggression as well as ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to hinder Western support for Georgia and prevent reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The powers that matter in Georgia are Russia and to a certain extent the United States.
Europe must show that it is also significant.
Estonia has – both during its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument – shown that one can resist Russian pressure with resolve and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this could be a means for Georgians to help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate grounds for hope that it will achieve genuine independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians ever were?
The lack of reform success is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
Dass sich die industrialisierte Region Transnistrien – deren russisch und ukrainisch sprechende Bevölkerung fürchtete, die Mehrheit der Moldauer, die rumänischer Abstammung ist, engere Verbindungen zu Rumänien – plane, von Moldau lossagte, hat der Unabhängigkeit des Landes gleich zu Beginn einen schweren Schlag versetzt.
Es folgte ein Bürgerkrieg, und im Jahre 1992 marschierten russische Truppen in Transnistrien ein, wo sie heute noch sind.
Die Unabhängigkeit Transnistriens wurde nie anerkannt – weder von Moldau noch international.
Es heißt, dort herrsche Gesetzlosigkeit und Korruption.
Moldau ist hochverschuldet, die Arbeitslosigkeit ist hoch, und seine einst renommierte Weinbranche befindet sich im Niedergang.
Russia occasionally cuts gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Moldovan government representatives have made four fruitless visits to Moscow to try to persuade President Vladimir Putin to work on a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
Voronin, in desperation, has asked for help from the EU observer force EUBAM, but an EU initiative would require Russian cooperation.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks up-to-date insights into the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and also the USA only learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leaky report that was published in Germany.
According to this, it seems that Russia would benefit from it, as the agreement is supposed to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate entity within Moldova.
If Russia has thus enticed the West in this way, it would be a disastrous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-communist states.
